For years, building an accessible modal required a UI library or hundreds of lines of JavaScript. The HTML `<dialog>` element gives us all of this natively.
## Basic Usage
```html
<dialog id="my-dialog">
  <h2>Dialog Title</h2>
  <p>This is a native modal dialog.</p>
  <button onclick="this.closest('dialog').close()">Close</button>
</dialog>

<button onclick="document.getElementById('my-dialog').showModal()">
  Open Dialog
</button>
```
Calling `showModal()` does everything a modal needs:
- Centers the dialog on screen
- Adds a backdrop overlay
- Traps focus inside the dialog
- Closes on Escape key
- Marks the rest of the page as `inert`
## Styling the Backdrop
The `::backdrop` pseudo-element lets you style the overlay:
```css
dialog::backdrop {
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  backdrop-filter: blur(4px);
}

dialog {
  border: none;
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 2rem;
  max-width: 480px;
  box-shadow: 0 8px 32px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
}
```
## Close on Backdrop Click
One thing `<dialog>` doesn't do by default is close when clicking the backdrop. Here's a clean way to add it:
```javascript
dialog.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
  if (e.target === dialog) {
    dialog.close();
  }
});
```
## Form Integration
Forms inside a dialog can use `method="dialog"` to close the dialog on submit and pass a return value:
```html
<dialog id="confirm">
  <form method="dialog">
    <p>Are you sure?</p>
    <button value="cancel">Cancel</button>
    <button value="confirm">Confirm</button>
  </form>
</dialog>
```
```javascript
const dialog = document.getElementById("confirm");
dialog.addEventListener("close", () => {
  console.log(dialog.returnValue); // "cancel" or "confirm"
});
```
## Animations
You can animate the dialog's entrance and exit with CSS:
```css
dialog[open] {
  animation: fade-in 0.2s ease-out;
}

@keyframes fade-in {
  from {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(-10px);
  }
  to {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
}
```
---
The `<dialog>` element is supported in all modern browsers. For most modal use cases, you no longer need a UI library — the platform handles accessibility, focus management, and keyboard interactions for free.
